        <h2>CEMS</h2>
        <p>
            Continuous Emissions Monitoring Systems (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continuous_emissions_monitoring_system">CEMS</a>) are tools used to gather valuable data from power plant <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flue_gas">flue gas</a> as a way to comply with the <a href="https://www.epa.gov/">United States Environmental Protection Agency's</a> <a href="https://www.epa.gov/airmarkets/acid-rain-program">Acid Rain Program</a> and other federal and state emission program/standards.
        </p>
        <hr />
        <h2>Goal</h2>
        <p>
            The purpose of CEMS Study&trade; is to provide valuable quick-reference material for individuals ranging from savvy CEMS professionals to the occasional environmentalist or CEMS newcomer.  Reference materials range from <a href="https://www.epa.gov/laws-regulations/regulations">40 CFR</a> regulations to <a href="https://ecmps.camdsupport.com/learn_intro.shtml">Emissions Collection and Monitoring Plan Systems (ECMPS)</a>.
        </p>
        <hr />
        <h2>Contact</h2>
        <p>
            If you wish to see any other CEMS-related information added to this site, please use the Contact link to submit your suggestions.  As always, your recommendations are greatly appreciated.
        </p>
        <p>
            @*TRIGGER CONTACT MODAL*@
